<HEAD>Kellogg Takes Nabisco to Court Over Shredded Wheat Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kellogg Co. is taking Nabisco Brands
to court over shredded wheat, contending Nabisco is trying to crush
Kellogg's plans to introduce a more nutritious cereal.
   Kellogg has been planning since June to put its Whole Grain
Shredded Wheat on the market this month with the claim it's ``very
simply, the most nutritious shredded wheat you can buy.''
   The company contends the shredded wheat has 33 percent more
dietary fiber and more thiamine, riboflavin, niacin, iron, vitamins
B6 and B12, folic acid, magnesium and zinc _ with no sugar or salt
_ than the famous shredded wheat manufactured for 89 years by New
Jersey-based Nabisco Brands, a division of RJR-Nabisco.
   But on July 27, attorneys for Nabisco told Kellogg that it, too,
had developed a more nutritious shredded wheat _ with nearly
identical nutritional value as the new Kellogg product _ that would
be on the market in mid-August.
   Nabisco sent a letter to Kellogg, saying the Battle Creek
company must ``take immediate steps to avoid any false claims of
nutritional superiority for its fortified shredded wheat cereal on
packaging, advertising, point of sale and any other materials
whatsoever.''
   Instead, Kellogg filed suit Aug. 3 in U.S. District Court in
Kalamazoo.
   The company contends Nabisco had known since early June that
Kellogg was preparing to spring the new shredded wheat onto the
market, but said nothing. Kellogg had been sending samples and
promotional materials since that time to various test markets.
   ``That Nabisco should wait for 89 years and a competitive
challenge from Kellogg before manufacturing its own unsugared,
fortified shredded wheat biscuit was itself suspicious,'' the suit
says. ``But ... Kellogg has learned other facts which clearly
indicate that Nabisco set out to copy both the features of and
marketing strategy behind Kellogg's new cereal in a cynical attempt
to prevent vigorous competition in a sector of the market for
ready-to-eat cereals that it has dominated for so long.''
   Nabisco spokesman Mark Gutsche said Friday the company denies
the charge and called the lawsuit ``a reaction to Nabisco's own
threat of legal action.''
   He said the company's new cereal, Spoon Size Plus Shredded
Wheat, a fortified version of its regular product, already has been
sent to grocers.
   ``Nabisco is absolutely confident that Kellogg will be stopped
from confusing consumers that its new cereal is the most nutritious
shredded wheat,'' he said, reading from a prepared statement.
   Kellogg spokesman Neil Nyberg said the company is asking the
court to rule that its product claims are legal and that Nabisco
may not sue Kellogg over those claims.
</TEXT>
