<HEAD>Leading Researcher Sues Science Academy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Academy of Sciences is fighting a
$500,000 lawsuit that claims it plagiarized the writings of a
nutrition researcher that it earlier had rejected.
   Victor Herbert, a lawyer and physician who filed the suit in
U.S. District Court, charged that the academy copied figures
verbatim on work he had done to update published recommended
dietary allowances (RDAs), after earlier trying to discredit the
work.
   ``Dr. Herbert is a great promoter of nutrition science,''
Herbert's attorney, Michael Botts, said in a telephone interview
Sunday from Kansas City, Mo. ``It isn't just a moral point at all.
(The academy) took his work and then went out and sold it. The
academy made in the neighborhood of a half million dollars off of
this work.''
   RDAs form the foundation for determining the nutritional needs
of schoolchildren, food stamp recipients and other federally funded
supplemental programs. The academy sells lists of the standards to
libraries, medical schools, doctors, dietitians and nutritionists.
   To update the RDAs in the mid-1980s, the science academy, an
independent federal agency chartered by Congress, selected Herbert
and nine other prominent nutrition scientists.
   Using a $650,000 grant from the National Institutes of Health,
the committee's produced a document that discussed the sciences of
each 18 essential vitamins and minerals that each person is
encouraged to eat each day.
   Botts claimed the academy tinkered with the RDAs document before
publishing it in October 1989, damaging the ``integrity of the
authors' work'' and destroying the quality.
   The document included copyrighted material Herbert wrote on iron
and on the vitamins B12 and folate, or folic acid, Botts said.
   Lawyers for the academy filed a motion for dismissal last week
and a hearing on the motion has been scheduled for Oct. 17. The
academy contends that if there is copyright infringement, the
federal government should be the defendant in the suit, which was
filed in February.
   Botts said the committee completed its work and passed peer
review, and a September 1985 publication date was scheduled. The
panel was prepared to recommend lower levels of vitamins A and C
than what had been suggested earlier.
   But according to Botts, the academy gave the panel an ultimatum:
keep the RDAs for vitamins A and C the same, while adding a
footnote to the table at the end of the book.
   When the academy and committee disagreed over the wording of the
footnote, the academy refused to publish the work and disbanded the
group, Botts said.
   Botts described the disagreement as ``a conflict in nutrition
between those who promote pop nutrition,'' such as those who call
for high doses of fiber and vitamin C versus those who say there is
harm in ingesting too much fiber and vitamin C.
   ``That's nonsense,'' Calvin H. Cobb Jr., a lawyer representing
the academy, was quoted as saying in Saturday editions of The
Washington Post. ``The complaint has no merit.''
   The National Institutes of Health in 1986 told the academy it
must fulfill the terms of the contract or return the money. Botts
said NIH officials reviewed the committee's report and wanted it to
be published but the academy said it needed $160,000 to select a
subcommittee to update the earlier work.
   Meanwhile, Botts said Herbert's work appeared in a nutrition
education journal in 1987.
   The academy published a 10th edition revision in October 1989.
Botts said the subcommittee was listed as author, although the work
included Herbert's writings.
