      Vaccine for Arthritis
   Shows Promise in Rats
   AN ARTHRITIS vaccine works in rats, suggesting a new avenue of research on human rheumatoid arthritis. 

   Human rheumatoid arthritis is thought to be an autoimmune disease in which the body mistakenly attacks its own joint cartilage, causing inflammation and destruction of the joints. 

   To study autoimmune arthritis, a team of Dutch and Israeli researchers induced the disease in susceptible laboratory rats by injecting them with a strain of bacteria. 
The rats' immune systems activated white blood cells that attacked both the bacteria and the rats' cartilage, causing the arthritis. 
The reseachers discovered that the white cells "recognized" and attacked a tiny segment of a protein on the bacteria. 
It turned out that a protein segment in cartilage is similar to the bacterial protein segment, which explained why the white cells also attacked the cartilage. 

   But the researchers also found a paradox: The same protein fragment also activated a second type of white blood cell that seemed to suppress the attack on cartilage. 
In fact, these cells prevented arthritis when given to rats before bacteria injections. 

   The puzzled researchers genetically engineered a version of the tiny protein fragment and injected it in rats to see if it caused or prevented arthritis. 
The protein fragment prevented the disease and even caused a remission in rats who had arthritis. 

   In their report in a recent issue of the journal Nature, the researchers note that the protein segment, or one closely related to it, is found in more than 50 species of bacteria, all of which have been suspected of being involved in rheumatoid arthritis. 
Perhaps, they speculated, bacterial infections in certain "susceptible" individuals trigger autoimmune arthritis. 
If this is true, they suggest, then a purified version of the protein fragment might suppress the disease as it did in the rats. 

   Athletes Wearing Black
   Play More Aggressively
   BLACK UNIFORMS make football and hockey players appear -- and act -- meaner, according to a study by two Cornell University psychologists. 

   Penalty records of 28 National Football League teams from 1970 to 1986 showed that all five teams that wore predominately black uniforms were among the 12 most penalized teams. 
Similarly, the three most penalized teams in the National Hockey League in those 17 years wore black. 
When the Pittsburgh Penguins switched to black-and-gold from blue in midseason in 1979-80 (to emulate that year's NFL champion Pittsburgh Steelers), their average penalty time per hockey game went to 12 minutes from eight minutes. 

   This prompted the psychologists to launch a series of experiments on the effects of black uniforms. 
Groups of football fans and referees were shown either of two videotapes of a staged football play. 
In one tape the defensive team wore black while in the other tape the defenders wore white. 
Those who saw the black-uniformed team rated the defenders as far more aggressive and "dirty" than those who watched the white-clothed defenders making the same moves. 

   Moreover, when student volunteers were asked to pick five games to play against a competing team, those given black jerseys tended to pick aggressive games like dart-gun duels, while those in white jerseys picked games like putting contests. 

   A black uniform may make others think a person is more aggressive or "mean" and, as a result, the person becomes more aggressive, the psychologists speculate in the Journal of Personality and Social Psychology. 

   Boosting Intelligence
   Vitamin by Vitamin
   CAN CHILDREN'S intelligence be improved by vitamin-mineral supplements? 

   Two psychologists in Wales sought to answer this question in an experiment with 90 students, aged 12 and 13. 
Diet diaries kept by the children before the experiment began indicated that they consumed on the average slightly less than recommended amounts of most minerals and several vitamins, particularly thiamine, folic acid and vitamin D. 

   For eight months 30 of the children took daily vitamin-mineral supplements, 30 took placebos and 30 were untreated. 
Intelligence tests showed that all the children had a slight increase in verbal intelligence, which needs vocabulary and real-world experience to solve problems. 

   But only the 30 children taking the supplements showed an improvement in non-verbal intelligence, the innate ability one uses to solve problems that don't require learning or experience, such as figuring out that a square peg goes into a square hole. 

   "Inadequate nutrition would be expected to show its earliest effects on the more biological intelligence measured by the non-verbal intelligence test," the psychologists note in the medical journal Lancet. 
The experiment suggests that less than optimum amounts of vitamins and minerals may be hampering the children's brain functioning, they say. 

   Nicotine Gum Becomes
   An Unexpected Habit
   IN BALTIMORE, a three-pack a-day smoker quit his 21-year habit by chewing Nicorette, the nicotine gum made by Dow Chemical Co.'s Lakeside Pharmaceutical division. 
But he became addicted to the gum, chewing 17 pieces a day, researchers at Johns Hopkins Medical School and the National Institute on Drug Abuse report in Lancet. 

   So the researchers gradually substituted the Nicorette in his daily ration with a placebo gum. 
After six weeks, he was chewing only the placebo. 
He then weaned himself off the placebo by substituting bubble gum. 
Lakeside says it hasn't any immediate plans to market a placebo Nicorette. 

