<HEAD>Sullivan Discusses Food-Labeling Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan on Tuesday disclosed additional details about the
food-labeling rules being drafted, but it's still undecided whether
they will apply uniformly.
   Sullivan declined to discuss the uniformity question during a
speech to a conference on food safety and nutrition, saying ``this
issue is under review within the administration.'' He also declined
to discuss it after his speech.
   Administration sources have said Sullivan's department wants the
federal regulations to supersede state regulations, but that White
House officials don't want to preclude the states from adding
stronger regulations.
   California is the only state that might be directly affected.
   Sullivan said he believed the uniformity question would be
resolved ``very soon.'' He previously said he wanted to get the
proposed regulations out by the end of this month, but he declined
Tuesday to be that specific.
   The proposal, to be issued by the Food and Drug Administration,
would require nutrition labeling on most foods _ including most
fresh produce and seafood.
   Nutrition labels would have to appear on all packaged food. For
unpackaged foods such as fresh fruits, vegetables and seafood,
other methods of displaying the information would be allowed, such
as leaflets or posters where the foods are sold.
   Also, manufacturers would have to show on the label the number
of calories from fat and the amount of saturated fatty acids,
cholesterol and total dietary fiber.
   The regulations would define the terms ``cholesterol free,''
``low cholesterol'' and ``reduced cholesterol'' to eliminate
misleading claims.
   Restaurants, bakeries, cafeterias and some small businesses
would be exempt from the regulations, Sullivan said. Also waived
from the requirements would be bite-size foods and foods that have
no meaningful sources of calories and nutrients, he said.
   Another change would update the reference values, now called the
Recommended Daily Allowance or RDA, used to compare the nutrition
content of foods and evaluate a food's contribution to the diet.
   RDA would be replaced with the term Reference Daily Intakes, or
RDI, and updated values would be proposed for protein and for 12
vitamins and seven minerals that have RDAs.
   Vitamin K, manganese and other nutrients that don't have RDAs
would be added to the list with reference values.
   Reference values also would be established for fat, cholesterol,
sodium and fiber, but manufacturers would not be required to
include that in their nutrition labels, Sullivan said.
   The food industry has lobbied strongly for a labeling policy
that would be standard across the country.
   John Cady, president of the National Food Processors
Association, said that if labeling rules differed from state to
state, consumers would be confused and distribution logistics would
increase food costs substantially.
   The Center for Science in the Public Interest wants the states
to be able to bolster any federal food-labeling requirements. But
even with that issue aside, center officials say the department's
proposals ``are inadequate given the severity of the problem.''
   Bruce Silverglade, legal affairs director for the center, said
the organization obtained a draft copy of some portions of the
proposed regulations. Because of several deficiencies in the
proposal, he said, the center is urging passage of congressional
legislation that is tougher.
   Silverglade said Sullivan's proposal was defective because it
would not require manufacturers to disclose how much fat,
cholesterol, sodium and fiber a food contributes to the maximum
daily amounts a person should consume. It also would not require
disclosure of sugar content or set a deadline for final agency
action, he said.
   Current requirements, established 17 years ago, call for
nutrition labeling only when a manufacturer adds vitamins, minerals
or proteins or makes a nutritional claim about the product.
   About 60 percent of packaged foods list nutrients, a majority of
which is labeled voluntarily.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

