<HEADLINE>
<P>
PANEL'S RECOMMENDATIONS ON VITAMINS FOR PREGNANT WOMEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The headline ("Skip Vitamins, Pregnant Women Told") and the lead in your 
front-page article were not fully in sync with all the information presented in 
the rest of the article -- including legitimate viewpoints favoring supplement 
use by pregnant women because of deficiencies in their diets. 
</P>
<P>
Many dietary surveys show a high frequency of deficient diets in the United 
States, with young women some of the worst offenders. 
</P>
<P>
Indeed, supplement use prevents certain birth defects. A recent signed 
editorial comment in the Journal of the American Medical Assn. stated, "The 
biggest challenge . . . about the benefits of taking vitamins is to get women 
of childbearing age to hear and follow this simple advice." 
</P>
<P>
The National Academy of Sciences committee members whose report you cited are 
not omniscient. Nutritionists with credentials equal or superior to theirs 
differ greatly over the benefits of supplement use by pregnant women. The 
committee is not even consistent -- concern with possible nutrient interaction 
(iron's interference with zinc absorption) was not reflected in its advice to 
take iron supplements during pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
Even though the committee admits to "considerable variation in nutrient 
requirements among individuals," its report failed to identify how physicians 
can determine their patients' requirements. In fact, no method that is both 
inexpensive and reliable is available. 
</P>
<P>
BURTON KALLMAN 
</P>
<P>
Director, Science and Technology 
</P>
<P>
National Nutritional Foods Assn. 
</P>
<P>
Costa Mesa 
</P>
